                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-537-18560514 t18560514-537-punishment-45"></join>Confined Twelve Months</rs>.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WAY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-452" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-452" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-452" type="surname" value="BROOM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-452" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY BROOM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of James Broom, I live at No. 2, Queen's-square, Bartholomew-close. On 30th April I was at the corner of Princes-street, Barbican, about 5 minutes past 11 o'clock at night, carrying a large bundle—I felt some one's hand on my shoulder, I turned, and saw the two</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140273"></xptr>
               <p>prisoners togethert—Combe disappeared, lie went off the pavement—Jones snatched my bundle, and they both ran together up Princes-street, and I after them—I ran into Charles-street, Bridgewater-square, and Combe came to me, and said, "What is the matter?"—I said, "Don't talk to me; why don't you catch that man that has got my bundle, which you know?"—he struck me in the face, and I fell down—I got up again, and ran after them—they were both running together down the street—they ran into Golden-lane, and I lost sight of them—from the time I first saw Combe till the time he struck me, I had not lost sight of him—I never lost sight of them till they got into Golden-lane—I saw them about an hour afterwards, I went with the policeman, and gave them into custody—I saw them at a lodging house in Golden-lane, with other persons—my bundle contained four frocks, seven pinafores, five aprons, and some other things—I had an opportunity of seeing the person of Combe before he struck me—he laid hold of my shawl, and I looked him in the face—I am quite sure he is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Combe. Q.</hi> I was sitting in the house, conversing with the woman who keeps the house, when you came in with the sergeant and two men, and took me; what time did you see me in the house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About an hour after I was robbed, about half past 12 o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-453" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-453" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-453" type="surname" value="DELLOW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-453" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DELLOW</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi>, 95). On 30th April I received infor<lb></lb>mation of this robbery from Mrs. Broom—she gave me a description of the persons who committed it—it was owing to that, that I took her to the lodging house in Golden-lane—I found the two prisoners in the house—they were recognized by the prosecutrix—as soon as she got a fair sight of their faces, she recognized them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Combe.</hi> She did not recognize me, she said I was not the man. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> She did recognize you—she said once tnat she did not think you were the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When was that? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> As soon as she went into the room I told him to step forward, and she said, "I don't think that that is the man;" but as soon as he came in sight of her, she said, "That is the man that knocked me down"—she recognized him as soon as she got a fair sight of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Combe. Q.</hi> You said, "Are you sure that that is anything like the man?" and she said, "Yes;" but did she not say five different times that I was not the man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-454" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-454" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-454" type="surname" value="DELLOW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-454" type="given" value="DAHIEL"></interp>DAHIEL DELLOW</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi>, 118). I was present on 30th April when the two prisoners were taken into custody—I heard the prosecutrix recognize them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-455" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-455" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-455" type="surname" value="EGERTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-455" type="given" value="FRANCES"></interp>FRANCES EGERTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Egerton—I live at No. 2, Queen-square, Bartholomew-close. On the night of 30th April I was with Mrs. Broom, at the corner of Princes-street—I saw Jones and another person with him, but whether it was Combe I could not say—I could not identify him—Jones snatched the bundle from the woman, and he ran away—the other party made towards Princes-street—Mrs. Broom had nearly overtaken tfcem, calling out, "Stop thief!"—I followed as quickly as I could, but they; had proceeded too far for me to see anything more done—the other person was the same size as Combe, as near as I could judge—I cannot swear to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Combes Defence.</hi> On the night of 30th April, while sitting in the house of Mrs. Gardner, three policemen came in, accompanied by Mrs. Broom; I being the nearest person to the police sergeant, he asked her if</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140274"></xptr>
               <p>there was any person in the room who robbed her; she said she did not know; I was asked to stand up, and I did; the policeman then asked her if I was the man, she said that she could not say; he asked her again if I was like the man; she said that she could not say and could not swear, five different times; I asked Mrs. Broom how long it was since it happened, she said about an hour; I said that I had been in the house more than that time; Mrs. Gardner also said that was not the man, meaning me, at the time; there were several more persons in the room at the tune, who said the same as Mrs. Gardner; one of the policemen then nodded to Mrs. Broom, and she directly said, "Yes, policeman, that is the man that knocked me down;" I then asked Mrs. Gardner if she would be so kind as to come to Guildhall in the morning to speak for me; she was outside the Court when I had my hearing; I was remanded for two days, and when I was brought up, Mrs. Gardner was in the Court; I called on her, and asked Alderman Muggeridge to have my witnesses sworn; he told me, not then, I might call them at Newgate, for he should send me for trial; I have sent to Mrs. Gardner since, and to my friends; I hare sent my friends to her, but her reply is that she would not come for 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the police have been there, so I doubt not but they have put a stop to her coming to prove my innocence; there are more men than me that dress like me in London, there are thousands; I can prove that I do not get my living by thieving; I have been at work for Mr. Henry Hartrey, of Bermondsey, the last six months, and I am not more than seven months from Ireland; I can look any policeman in the face, and bid defiance to any one to say he knows me.</p>
               <p>
